in our system landscape, and sometimes we have to resort to Java to be really compliant with

00:12:30.760 --> 00:12:40.280
all the regulations that we have in the industry. I see Adam has a follow-up question here. Adam,

00:12:40.280 --> 00:12:44.039
you want to jump in? Yeah, I think that's interesting. I'm always thinking about that

00:12:44.039 --> 00:12:50.119
idea of polyglot workflows and how you mix languages, and that's something that I'm kind

00:12:50.119 --> 00:12:55.640
of passionate about because I feel like we did it mostly successfully in a previous role,

00:12:55.640 --> 00:12:59.799
but I know that there are lots of challenges that also make it kind of hard. I'm curious

00:12:59.799 --> 00:13:03.000
what your main challenges were and why you kind of are moving away from that.

00:13:05.640 --> 00:13:11.400
Well, one of the challenges was package management and dependency management. So

00:13:11.880 --> 00:13:19.719
if you have both languages, you just have to manage more potential holes when you go to ITsec

00:13:19.719 --> 00:13:27.799
for clearance to go into production. So that's just a lot of work. It also has implications

00:13:27.799 --> 00:13:33.640
on the kind of documentation we have to do. It's just more documentation if you use many

00:13:33.640 --> 00:13:40.679
different languages. And it's also just the switching costs. So if one and the same person,

00:13:40.679 --> 00:13:46.119
even if he or she is fluent in both languages, just switches intraday between languages,

00:13:46.679 --> 00:13:54.039
people just felt that that is just a friction in their everyday working that isn't necessary.

00:13:55.320 --> 00:13:58.200
In the beginning, it made sense because when we started off, we were like

00:13:58.919 --> 00:14:04.119
four, five, six people doing that. So one had a Python background and another had an

00:14:04.119 --> 00:14:09.159
R background, and we had to throw that all together in the first project. But as we grew,

00:14:09.799 --> 00:14:16.119
we had subgroups who focused on one of the languages, and then it was more natural to

00:14:16.119 --> 00:14:21.080
stay within that context in that one language per project. So maybe it's also a function of

00:14:21.080 --> 00:14:28.200
the size of the team. Yeah, that makes sense. I'm just a heavy R user in an increasingly Python

00:14:28.200 --> 00:14:33.640
world, so I'm always thinking about that. Thank you. Yeah, same for me. I mean, I feel most at

00:14:33.640 --> 00:14:42.200
home in R. The marketing mix model we're building, which I'm closest to in my data science

00:14:42.200 --> 00:14:52.840
work, is also completely in R. So that's my home zone. But I have to remind myself to stay fit in

00:14:52.840 --> 00:15:00.119
Python. We'll stay on this topic for a little bit because I see Alan had a follow-up here too.

