Nice. Thank you. That's really, really interesting. Appreciate it.

00:18:07.479 --> 00:18:14.359
I see a few questions coming in around modeling, and I don't know, Saptarishi,

00:18:14.359 --> 00:18:18.280
do you want to kick us off with your question there on the marketing mixed model?

00:18:19.719 --> 00:18:25.239
Sure, yeah. Hi. I just graduated recently with a master's in marketing analytics,

00:18:25.239 --> 00:18:31.160
and something that we just touched is marketing mixed modeling. I wanted to learn a bit more

00:18:31.160 --> 00:18:36.920
about what kind of tools you use for working with marketing mixed modeling, Benedikt. You

00:18:36.920 --> 00:18:40.839
said you use R primarily, but could you tell us a bit more about that?

00:18:41.400 --> 00:18:51.239
Yeah, sure. So the starting point was Facebook's Robin model. So we have a mostly R set up there,

00:18:51.239 --> 00:18:56.760
and if you go through it line by line, you get a really good feeling about how to do

00:18:59.479 --> 00:19:07.880
the various parts that are required, like ad stocking and what are parts of a good marketing

00:19:07.880 --> 00:19:18.040
mixed model. Now, one of the things from this first experience with Robin that didn't work well

00:19:18.040 --> 00:19:24.359
for us was we had the requirement that we, on the one hand, wanted to know what the effects of our

00:19:24.359 --> 00:19:30.119
brand are on sales, but also we wanted to know what the effects of performance marketing, like

00:19:30.119 --> 00:19:36.199
search advertising, are on sales, and we wanted to have that in the same model. If you go to an agency

00:19:36.199 --> 00:19:40.520
and buy a marketing mixed model, you usually get two different models, one for the performance

00:19:40.520 --> 00:19:47.319
marketing and another maybe structural equation model for the brand part, because that's longer

00:19:47.319 --> 00:19:56.359
term. That was the initiator for us to build our own model, and one of the central requirements to

00:19:56.359 --> 00:20:04.599
have a marketing mixed model that we can refresh every day. I mean, if the search colleagues come

00:20:04.599 --> 00:20:10.680
to me and have launched a new campaign, and a few days after that they come to me and want to know

00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:16.439
whether their campaign works, whether I see any differences in the marginal contributions of the

00:20:16.439 --> 00:20:22.599
different campaigns to sales, well, it's no good if I have to tell them, well, come back in half a year,

00:20:22.599 --> 00:20:28.280
because that's the refresh rate of the model, and then we have weekly data, which is the usual

00:20:28.280 --> 00:20:34.760
thing you do for marketing mixed model. That was one of the main requirements,

00:20:35.400 --> 00:20:40.040
and also one of the main challenges, because we needed daily data, not just from the standard

00:20:40.040 --> 00:20:47.640
APIs from Google and Meta, but also from our agencies, which had hundreds of sub-agencies and

00:20:48.520 --> 00:20:53.000
advertisers where they needed to gather their data, so that was quite a data engineering effort

00:20:53.719 --> 00:21:01.160
to get all that together, and then you have to do model adjustments. For example, one of the

00:21:01.160 --> 00:21:07.719
central questions for the model are time-varying coefficients for the model,

00:21:07.719 --> 00:21:13.160
so if you use a standard marketing mixed model, you get one coefficient for one channel, that's what

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:19.079
Robin does, for example, but if you want to do a daily model, and you want the model to pick up changes,

00:21:19.880 --> 00:21:26.760
then you can't have one coefficient for the whole time period, say a year, on a daily basis,

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:32.680
because then you don't see any differences, so you want to see these coefficients change in the model,

00:21:32.680 --> 00:21:39.319
and there was a lot of experimenting with the feature engineering and how to get the GLM net

00:21:39.319 --> 00:21:45.000
parameters just about right, that these differences in coefficients come up in the model.

00:21:46.040 --> 00:21:53.800
There are lots of other tinkerings and bits, for example, we played around with causal inference,

00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:59.719
because we had a lot of sales process data, and just threw that out of the window for the

00:21:59.719 --> 00:22:06.040
standard models with Robin, so we integrated a few different formulas and a few

00:22:09.319 --> 00:22:16.680
mediating models that represented the process steps in the causal inference chain that we had

00:22:16.680 --> 00:22:25.160
in theory, at least in our sales process, and then we can better isolate the effects to make that more

00:22:26.119 --> 00:22:36.599
... to illustrate that in one of the first iterations of this model, we had a quite strong

00:22:36.599 --> 00:22:45.560
impact from social, from organic social posts on sales. Later on in the model, we implemented,

00:22:45.560 --> 00:22:52.520
we also added our internal email campaignings to the model, that weren't part of the initial data

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:57.959
engineering effort and weren't there at the beginning, and then we saw from, while analyzing

00:22:57.959 --> 00:23:03.319
the causal inference chain of all these intermediate models and the chain, that the

00:23:03.319 --> 00:23:12.680
effect of the email campaigns controlled, when controlling for social posts on sales, was greater

00:23:12.680 --> 00:23:19.479
than the effect of social posts on sales controlled for email campaigns, which was an indicator that

00:23:19.479 --> 00:23:26.280
our social, organic social posts reached at least partly our existing customers, which still drove

00:23:26.280 --> 00:23:33.239
engagement, but didn't drive additional sales. So that's an, that was an interesting discussion

00:23:33.239 --> 00:23:38.040
with our marketing colleagues, how we could readjust the targeting of those posts, for example.

00:23:40.199 --> 00:23:43.319
I was actually just going to ask you that, like how does some of the,

00:23:44.040 --> 00:23:49.000
how does the model change the actions of the team, like can you share an example of that?

00:23:49.800 --> 00:23:56.359
Yeah, sure. So that was, that was the beginning of one of the examples. So in the development phase,

00:23:56.359 --> 00:24:03.400
we had this, this very short feedback loop where we would work on the model each day and just

00:24:03.959 --> 00:24:11.719
send two or one or two output plots of the contributions of different marketing campaigns

00:24:11.719 --> 00:24:20.599
to sales, just to our then head of marketing. And he would just, just via, via a team chat,

00:24:20.599 --> 00:24:25.800
and he would just give us very quick reactions like total crap. I don't understand this.

00:24:25.800 --> 00:24:32.520
This isn't, this isn't possible. How can we have negative sales there? Why do we have a

00:24:32.520 --> 00:24:38.439
contribution from something we do not spend any money on? So it also helped, helped us fix issues

00:24:38.439 --> 00:24:47.079
in the data engineering part. But it also just transferred to us a lot of domain knowledge about

00:24:47.079 --> 00:24:56.599
marketing that we didn't have. And also transferred hopefully to, to them a bit of how, what,

00:24:56.599 --> 00:25:01.959
how we looked at the data, what kind of insights we were trying to get. And after, I don't know,

00:25:02.920 --> 00:25:08.839
50, 60, 70 of these exchanges, so it was for a time, it was just every day,

00:25:10.599 --> 00:25:19.560
the pictures started to synchronize. So we didn't, we, we, we had contributions from channels that

00:25:19.560 --> 00:25:26.119
they invested in. And we, we had one of few surprises and when they changed something,

00:25:26.599 --> 00:25:31.640
we could see something. And when we said, try this or that, and they tried, we could

00:25:31.640 --> 00:25:36.199
see a difference in the model. And that's, that helped a lot with the acceptance of those.

00:25:39.239 --> 00:25:42.599
I'll echo what Alan said in the chat. It seems like you have a great partnership

00:25:42.599 --> 00:25:49.640
with the team. Yeah, definitely. I mean, we've been working with that team and with a lot of

00:25:49.640 --> 00:25:56.920
other teams as well, but with that specific team for the last seven years, wasn't, wasn't the first

00:25:56.920 --> 00:26:03.160
effort to build a marketing model, a marketing mix model. And the first efforts didn't go as well.

00:26:04.439 --> 00:26:07.880
But we finally found an approach that worked. Yeah.

00:26:10.119 --> 00:26:12.680
Sam, I see you have your hand raised. Do you want to jump in here next?

00:26:13.400 --> 00:26:18.119
Yes. So my question was quite long. I'm trying to simplify it in a way that's more tangible.

00:26:19.319 --> 00:26:26.040
So I work for a health authority that runs about seven hospitals in BC, Canada. And right now,

00:26:26.040 --> 00:26:30.439
our senior executives are thinking about an AI platform. And so the complexity is we have a

00:26:30.439 --> 00:26:34.599
bunch of models that we're probably going to, and it's a small piece of it, right? Where it's going

00:26:34.599 --> 00:26:41.160
to be handled, tracked, and they can be either private providers, custom built, or they can be

00:26:41.160 --> 00:26:47.479
private providers, custom built into in-house. And the question is, how are you managing them?

00:26:47.479 --> 00:26:54.760
Like we, I'm recommending Weights & Bias, MLflow, or Neptune AI, some kind of already available

00:26:54.760 --> 00:27:01.319
framework and use that to manage the custom models or vendor models. The other question is,

00:27:02.680 --> 00:27:06.920
you know, there are so many models coming in from various departments internally in your

00:27:06.920 --> 00:27:12.760
organization. Like, how do you know what's what and how do you keep track? Do you guys do it

00:27:12.760 --> 00:27:16.760
your way or you have these third-party providers? That's my question. Sorry. Thanks.

00:27:21.319 --> 00:27:30.359
I wouldn't say there's one way to solve all these problems. In a way, it depends.

00:27:30.920 --> 00:27:38.839
So what we do to manage the model in a way depends on the application or the area of application.

00:27:39.479 --> 00:27:47.239
So there are models that just are meant as decision support or informing decisions.

00:27:47.239 --> 00:27:57.319
And for those models, the regulatory requirements are not as high as for other models. So we try to

00:27:57.319 --> 00:28:03.160
keep the regulation overhead low while still fulfilling all the requirements that we got,

00:28:03.160 --> 00:28:12.199
which are still enough. But for those models, usually it's enough to have the code versions,

00:28:13.400 --> 00:28:20.920
to have version tracking for the different model iterations. And just, for example, upload those

00:28:20.920 --> 00:28:30.920
models into GitLab and use a GitLab runner and have a schedule there. So that's one of the simple

00:28:30.920 --> 00:28:40.920
cases. For the more critical applications, MLflow is one of the alternatives that we use. I would

00:28:40.920 --> 00:28:47.560
assume that we will use it in the future even more than we do now with new incoming regulation

00:28:47.560 --> 00:28:55.160
coming from the AI Act. So that we also need to take, for example, all the experiments

00:28:56.280 --> 00:29:05.560
and all of this. And for the most critical applications, we, for example, when we build

00:29:05.560 --> 00:29:14.199
models that help with pricing, they are integrated into the production pipeline from our pricing

00:29:14.199 --> 00:29:21.160
software, which is specialized insurance software. So we adapt to that format. And you have, of

00:29:21.160 --> 00:29:28.119
course, to invest time and resources to find a good way to, for example, extract the information

00:29:28.119 --> 00:29:35.479
from your model via PMML or something like that, or even cleverer formats and get that into a

00:29:35.479 --> 00:29:44.359
proprietary software suite. We don't rely that heavily on third-party models.

00:29:45.239 --> 00:29:51.640
Well, it changes a bit with LLMs, but that's a special case right now. Apart from that, we don't

00:29:51.640 --> 00:30:00.520
really rely on third-party models. One reason is governance and trustworthiness. So we want to have

00:30:00.520 --> 00:30:05.800
the full control over what the model does. Of course, also the full responsibility, ensuring

00:30:06.520 --> 00:30:16.599
that they are compliant. But also, I'm really skeptical about vendor lock-in and possible

00:30:16.599 --> 00:30:29.719
cost cuts that will then disable you from building new use cases. So for me, it also has to do with

00:30:29.719 --> 00:30:36.599
this robustness to be able to help yourself and build use cases in the future, not dependent on

00:30:36.599 --> 00:30:42.599
one single tool and maybe one discussion or management decision from one tool to another.

00:30:42.599 --> 00:30:45.959
So I don't want to be dependent on a proprietary tool.

00:30:49.479 --> 00:30:55.079
Thank you. I see, John, you had two questions. So maybe start with whichever one

00:30:55.800 --> 00:30:59.640
you want to ask here first. No, I appreciate it. Maybe I can merge them into one.

00:31:00.280 --> 00:31:04.439
So I'm starting a data team myself. I'm hiring up a few people. And I was wondering if you had

00:31:04.439 --> 00:31:08.839
some perspective, since your team is obviously much, much larger, on just how to set up the

00:31:08.839 --> 00:31:14.040
team itself, right? So things like, are you having some people specialize in interfacing

00:31:14.040 --> 00:31:19.160
with the business, like with marketing? Or is it everyone's doing that, or some people

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:23.160
sitting in the corner doing more of the hardcore analytics? So I'm just thinking about the titles

00:31:23.160 --> 00:31:26.359
and the structure and the organization design. I was hoping you could give a few insights.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:34.359
Yeah, sure. Maybe I start with one or two principles we have, and then the structure

00:31:35.400 --> 00:31:43.400
will fall into place. So I said at the beginning that I think it's important to keep things as

00:31:43.400 --> 00:31:49.000
interesting as possible for the individual data scientists. So one of our principles was,

00:31:49.000 --> 00:31:54.359
anybody is, in principle, allowed to do anything, to work on anything. So I don't want to have a

00:31:54.359 --> 00:32:01.719
setup that prohibits anybody to look into a topic or a potential model or use case that he or she

00:32:01.719 --> 00:32:07.959
finds interesting, or acquire a skill, a technical skill, that he or she finds relevant and interesting.

00:32:09.560 --> 00:32:17.319
The other principle is that the best use cases start from business questions. So I do not want

00:32:17.400 --> 00:32:29.160
to be merely a business support function. I want to be part of the business. I want to

00:32:29.160 --> 00:32:38.119
incentivize everybody in the teams to not just build the model, to have the attitude,

00:32:39.000 --> 00:32:43.079
give me the problem and I'll build you the model. So that's not the right attitude. You have to

00:32:43.560 --> 00:32:48.760
want people to solve the business problem so that they are really part of the business.

00:32:48.760 --> 00:32:53.959
It also gets you a seat at the table when the business decision comes along. So that's a

00:32:53.959 --> 00:33:05.800
benefit of that approach. So with that in mind, we had our team set up along the axis for whom

00:33:05.800 --> 00:33:16.839
are we working. So we have one team that focuses on gaining insights for human consumption.

00:33:16.839 --> 00:33:21.880
And we have another team that's more focused on building models. And the third team that

00:33:22.599 --> 00:33:29.719
focuses on applications that use ML models. Naturally, the first of these teams,

00:33:29.719 --> 00:33:37.160
so the insights focus team, is closer to departments like marketing or various other

00:33:37.160 --> 00:33:42.040
business functions. Or the last of these three teams is closer to an IT function.

00:33:43.160 --> 00:33:51.239
But it helps us also to avoid handoffs, for example, to IT or handoffs between the teams,

00:33:51.239 --> 00:33:57.400
because we can just create virtual teams between these three teams for any task that comes up.

00:33:58.280 --> 00:34:03.880
So it feels a bit complex, but it forces everybody to work across teams all the time,

00:34:03.880 --> 00:34:05.719
which I believe is a huge benefit.

00:34:09.479 --> 00:34:15.479
Absolutely. Love that. Going back to the mixed model for a second here,

00:34:15.479 --> 00:34:18.520
I see Renhua, you had a question. Want to jump in?

00:34:18.840 --> 00:34:26.120
I'm Renhua, I'm a data scientist in Calgary. And I have a question. I have a background for

00:34:26.120 --> 00:34:36.840
SAS and R and Python. And I tested the operation for the mixed model. And I think R is more like

00:34:36.840 --> 00:34:44.520
I have some kind of package very similar to SAS. And Python is, I think, is a

00:34:45.159 --> 00:34:53.879
I try to do this through the R, Python to be able to load in through the R to run the model.

00:34:55.239 --> 00:35:05.560
And I found that when I use R or Python, I think, how to say, they have some string testing

00:35:05.800 --> 00:35:17.959
that SAS is missing in R. So I think, what do you think about this kind of platform?

00:35:17.959 --> 00:35:23.159
And what do you think about stability after you build a model and how stable it is?

00:35:24.840 --> 00:35:30.760
Okay, that's a good question. Now, if I work on the model,

00:35:31.479 --> 00:35:42.120
I have to be really careful. So we have implemented a lot of tests, because there are parts of the

00:35:42.120 --> 00:35:53.159
model that can make the model really unstable. And it's quite hard for me to predict where this

00:35:53.159 --> 00:35:59.719
instability occurs. I think that over time, I've gotten an intuition about that.

00:36:00.919 --> 00:36:08.439
But still, if you, for example, play around with the lambda parameter of GLM net,

00:36:09.239 --> 00:36:16.360
and you just have the bad luck to get the wrong three lambda parameters,

00:36:16.360 --> 00:36:23.639
then the model output is totally different. To avoid that, one of the strategies to avoid that

00:36:23.639 --> 00:36:32.919
is that we do not really build a single model, but a whole host of models and have them consent

00:36:33.719 --> 00:36:40.120
on one view, how the channels are broken up and how we calculate the different contributions.

00:36:40.919 --> 00:36:49.080
And one of the other mechanisms that I like is that we use the marketing

00:36:49.560 --> 00:36:56.679
spendings in the past from our marketing colleagues as a guidance to what the most

00:36:56.679 --> 00:37:03.399
plausible model is. So we have the baseline model, which is just only looking at the data, not at how

00:37:05.000 --> 00:37:12.840
marketing thinks the contributions should be. But then within the distance from this

00:37:13.639 --> 00:37:21.879
best performing model, when it comes to RMSAE or the metrics, we search for a model that is

00:37:21.879 --> 00:37:28.120
most plausible, given the expertise of our marketers, that is also represented in how

00:37:28.120 --> 00:37:34.360
they spent their budgets in the past. And this also helps, of course, with the acceptance of the model.

00:37:34.520 --> 00:37:39.320
Thank you.

00:37:41.399 --> 00:37:45.800
Batul, I see you had a question that might be a follow-up here. Do you want to jump in next?

00:37:47.320 --> 00:37:53.239
Sure. Hello, everyone. I'm a data scientist at John Deere. So the two questions that I had is,

00:37:54.040 --> 00:38:00.679
how does your team, specifically individuals coming with native exploratory data analytics

00:38:00.679 --> 00:38:07.399
experience using R, transition into doing that with Python? As I do machine learning models

00:38:07.399 --> 00:38:13.639
myself and try to explore data, I feel I need to go to R, do my exploratory data analysis before

00:38:13.639 --> 00:38:21.239
I build models with Python or PySpark. So what's the strategy to easily transition to Python and

00:38:21.239 --> 00:38:26.679
do that easily? Second question is, going back to your question on the model coefficients,

00:38:27.479 --> 00:38:32.919
how often should a model be updated to capture the changes if we know that the data is going to be

00:38:32.919 --> 00:38:51.159
changing continuously? I don't feel that people in our teams really have to switch between R and

00:38:51.159 --> 00:39:01.000
Python when they go from EDA to building the model. But I see differences in how they do EDA,

00:39:02.199 --> 00:39:09.879
depending on whether they use R or Python. So if I have an R user, I probably get an R notebook or

00:39:09.879 --> 00:39:17.159
quarter notebook with a few ggplots, maybe not so much interactivity and rarely get a

00:39:17.159 --> 00:39:24.439
shiny dashboard for IDA. So maybe that's then people just moving on to Superset and doing

00:39:24.439 --> 00:39:32.919
the stuff there. If I have, if I see an EDA in Python, it's more likely to be interactive

00:39:32.919 --> 00:39:41.879
using Dash or maybe it's even demo-like as a streamlined app. So the starting point is

00:39:41.879 --> 00:39:55.239
probably more closer to the actual development. Since we stay within one language for the project,

00:39:56.040 --> 00:40:04.520
we don't switch within the project. But maybe there's a design part of our engineering or

00:40:04.520 --> 00:40:12.520
development cycle that helps there, because most of our use cases are created after a manual

00:40:12.520 --> 00:40:18.040
analysis. So most of the time we have just a business question that pops up when we do

00:40:18.040 --> 00:40:26.360
reporting or just manual analysis. We go into that question using proprietary tools like Google

00:40:26.439 --> 00:40:32.840
Analytics or the tracking solution that we have, which is a different one, or SAS maybe,

00:40:35.000 --> 00:40:41.719
and partially R there. And then when we discuss whether this can become a model or a use case,

00:40:41.719 --> 00:40:48.040
and we do the business, the cost-benefit ratio and all the analysis we have to do before we

00:40:48.040 --> 00:40:53.000
actually start a use case, then we have a different discussion of whether we keep it in R

00:40:53.879 --> 00:41:02.360
or do it in Python. And that takes away this switching pain from EDA to model development,

00:41:02.360 --> 00:41:11.879
a bit at least. Second question again was... It was about how often should the model be trained

00:41:11.879 --> 00:41:19.560
or retrained or updated to capture changes? Yeah. So the model is built with the time-varying

00:41:19.959 --> 00:41:27.719
coefficients in a way that it can adapt to changes itself. So we don't have to retrain

00:41:27.719 --> 00:41:37.479
everything all the time. As a matter of fact, we do it roughly once a week, I would say. So

00:41:38.120 --> 00:41:46.840
every time a change in the variables comes up, that triggers the tests and gives us a heads-up

00:41:46.840 --> 00:41:52.679
that we have something out of the standard deviation, we should consider retraining. So

00:41:52.679 --> 00:41:57.159
usually we do it then because it's not very expensive. Okay. Thank you.

00:41:58.840 --> 00:42:04.280
I'd love to see the questions to everybody in the chat as well. I saw Amiko asked a question

00:42:04.280 --> 00:42:10.520
to everybody if you want to weigh in, but tips on how you convince to be a part of the business

00:42:10.520 --> 00:42:17.560
instead of support. And so I see a thread there starting, but Benedikt, do you have anything you

00:42:17.560 --> 00:42:22.520
would want to add to that or tips on being a part of the business instead of support?

00:42:30.040 --> 00:42:37.000
So one of the things I see, particularly in people who are new to, who come newly into the

00:42:37.000 --> 00:42:45.959
team and aren't, maybe even from the industry, what happens a lot if you build dashboards or

00:42:45.959 --> 00:42:55.639
reports without industry experience is that you talk about the what that you see in the data.

00:42:56.360 --> 00:43:02.600
So you have, in principle, somebody reading out a dashboard to you. That may be interesting and

00:43:02.600 --> 00:43:06.439
the dashboard may look nice, but that's not really interesting for the business.

00:43:07.479 --> 00:43:13.320
They can, most of the time, they are quite quantitative. So they see the what immediately

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:21.239
and most of the time, even better than I would, for example. But the why is actually the important

00:43:21.239 --> 00:43:27.560
question and you don't normally get to the why if you just look at the data, you have to get out of

00:43:27.560 --> 00:43:34.360
your data science home zone area in the office and just go to the people who do the real work.

00:43:35.800 --> 00:43:42.679
And you come most of the time back with quite a few number of hypotheses about what's going wrong

00:43:42.679 --> 00:43:47.560
or what's going right about that. Of course, you can then think about designing experiments.

00:43:48.199 --> 00:43:57.399
But most of the time, if you just dig deep into the data, you can find a quite obvious

00:43:57.399 --> 00:44:03.959
answer that part of the process is just maybe broken or just faster than another process.

00:44:08.120 --> 00:44:14.360
So this obsession with getting to the why and getting your hands dirty in non-data science

00:44:14.360 --> 00:44:21.000
work, I think that's most important to be part of the business because everybody else in the

00:44:21.000 --> 00:44:28.120
business does it as well. You're not in a better position or you're not allowed to have

00:44:28.120 --> 00:44:31.479
any kind of attitude just because you're a data scientist.

00:44:34.679 --> 00:44:40.919
Thank you so much. A question I wanted to ask you and I think I see a few questions coming in

00:44:40.919 --> 00:44:48.199
about AI, but I haven't explicitly seen AI called out in as many head of analytics titles yet. And

00:44:48.199 --> 00:44:52.199
so I was wondering if you could just share a little bit more about that and the work that

00:44:52.199 --> 00:45:02.520
you're doing with AI. Sure. So one of the focus areas of right now is, of course, generative AI.

00:45:02.679 --> 00:45:11.800
And it's part of, well, it was borne out of last year's hype about that kind of artificial

00:45:11.800 --> 00:45:19.959
intelligence. We are currently, for example, working on a system that helps us retrieve

00:45:19.959 --> 00:45:28.919
knowledge from these very old insurance policies, which our customer agents spent quite some time on.

00:45:29.000 --> 00:45:42.199
We have various, very complex and partially very old knowledge databases where our customer

00:45:42.199 --> 00:45:48.040
agents have to gather multiple information across, I don't know, five databases to answer

00:45:48.040 --> 00:45:53.719
a question if it's really, really complicated. And they need then maybe even two or three other

00:45:53.719 --> 00:46:00.439
colleagues to be really precise about the answer. Because if you are not precise,

00:46:00.439 --> 00:46:07.239
then the company is, of course, liable for every false statement that the customer agent makes.

00:46:08.360 --> 00:46:17.879
And we are currently in the process of building a retrieval augmented generation stack to help

00:46:18.439 --> 00:46:25.080
get to the right documents faster. We're also experimenting with generating the answer.

00:46:25.080 --> 00:46:30.199
We have to be very cautious about that because of the liability issues.

00:46:31.560 --> 00:46:40.360
We are currently also very careful not to expose that to the end customer. I want to have

00:46:40.360 --> 00:46:46.760
a competent human always in between to check that. It's still in the development phase.

00:46:47.879 --> 00:46:53.320
But that's one of the main use cases where we use LLMs and general AI.

00:46:56.919 --> 00:47:01.719
Thank you. Abigail, I think you have a follow-up on this specific question. You want to jump in?

00:47:02.360 --> 00:47:06.280
Yeah, thanks. So I guess what is your architectural look broadly for your

00:47:06.280 --> 00:47:10.600
RAG chatbots and what are you doing for evaluation versus for formal assessments?

00:47:11.399 --> 00:47:21.800
Mm-hmm. So we use quite a standard RAG architecture with an external API call

00:47:23.800 --> 00:47:30.679
to open AI at the moment, but we're evaluating switching models there. We are

00:47:31.639 --> 00:47:41.639
estimating four metrics, if I remember correctly, at the same time. So factual correctness is one,

00:47:41.639 --> 00:47:50.120
relevance, conciseness, and completeness is the third, which I always find the hardest

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:59.239
when it comes to completeness. Because insurance policies for our flagship product are 277 pages

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:07.239
for one product. And it's hard to find out just how much text you quote and how much options and

00:48:07.239 --> 00:48:15.080
writers and exclusions you add to the answer you want to generate without overloading the whole

00:48:15.080 --> 00:48:21.000
chat. And it would be useless. People could just read all the pages and they wouldn't speed up in

00:48:21.000 --> 00:48:28.280
their operative process. So it's hard to get that right. And it varies with the stakeholder you're

00:48:28.280 --> 00:48:34.919
talking to. That's a different kind of challenge, but it's also a challenge if I talk to custom

00:48:34.919 --> 00:48:43.239
agents. They want different things than if I talk to product experts. And maybe it would be best to

00:48:43.239 --> 00:48:53.159
switch interfaces. I don't know yet. Thank you. Maximilian, I just want to make sure that that

00:48:53.159 --> 00:49:02.199
also covered your question. Yeah, I think so. Maybe just a follow-up question on that. Greetings

00:49:02.199 --> 00:49:09.239
from Munich, by the way. Did you also think about gen AI in combination with your predictive model?

00:49:09.239 --> 00:49:14.280
So you work a lot with marketing models, next best action, next best offer. And did you think about

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:20.199
using them in order to maybe explain the output a bit better or creating content around it?

00:49:20.760 --> 00:49:27.159
Hmm. Um, I haven't really, really invested deeply into that. So when we,

00:49:28.120 --> 00:49:32.840
we are thinking about one use case where we create content for campaigns.

00:49:34.919 --> 00:49:41.800
Um, I haven't really tried out creating explanations for the models. Um,

00:49:43.639 --> 00:49:45.479
maybe I should give it a go. Good thought.

00:49:45.879 --> 00:49:49.560
Awesome. Um, Rick, I see your hands raised. Want to jump in here next?

00:49:52.040 --> 00:49:58.679
Thank you, Rachel. Good to see you again. And Benedict, thank you. Uh, by the way, in the chat,

00:49:59.239 --> 00:50:05.879
spellcheck stumped on your name. I apologize on behalf of the rudimentary AI behind spellcheck.

00:50:07.080 --> 00:50:12.919
Uh, your remarks about getting to why are brilliant and, uh,

00:50:13.719 --> 00:50:19.719
personally, I'm a fan of causal inference. I'm wondering to what degree,

00:50:20.520 --> 00:50:25.639
and you also mentioned causal inference earlier in your remark. Would you please elaborate on

00:50:25.639 --> 00:50:32.199
the extent to which you and your team, uh, employ causal inference in your SD work?

00:50:33.080 --> 00:50:40.600
Um, I'm sorry, your DS work. Does your team embrace professor Pearl's the book of why

